#. <section class="sutta" id="sn47.6"><article><div class="hgroup"><p class="division">
msgctxt "sn47.6:0.1"
msgid "Saṃyutta Nikāya 47"
msgstr "Linked Discourses 47"

#. </p><p>
msgctxt "sn47.6:0.2"
msgid "1. Ambapālivagga"
msgstr "1. In Ambapālī’s Wood"

#. </p><h1>
msgctxt "sn47.6:0.3"
msgid "6. Sakuṇagghisutta"
msgstr "6. A Hawk"

#. </h1></div><p>
#. <a class="pts-vp-pi" id="pts-vp-pi5.147"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc1"></a>
msgctxt "sn47.6:1.1"
msgid ""
"“Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ sahasā ajjhappattā "
"aggahesi."
msgstr ""
"“Once upon a time, mendicants, a hawk suddenly swooped down and grabbed a "
"quail."

# Here I use gendered pronouns to clrify the narrative. The cases don’t necessarily imply the gender of the birds, though.
msgctxt "sn47.6:1.2"
msgid ""
"Atha kho, bhikkhave, lāpo sakuṇo sakuṇagghiyā hariyamāno evaṃ paridevasi:"
msgstr "And as the quail was being carried off he wailed:"

# I think translating appapunna, as BB does, with “of little merit” invites misinterpretation. I think this idiom has as little to do with Buddhist notions of “merit” (= good deeds) as the English “OMG” has with Catholic theology.
#. VAR: mayamevamha → mayamevāmha (mr)
msgctxt "sn47.6:1.3"
msgid ""
"‘mayamevamha alakkhikā, mayaṃ appapuññā, ye mayaṃ agocare carimha paravisaye."
msgstr ""
"‘I’m so unlucky, so unfortunate, to have roamed out of my territory into the "
"domain of others."

#. VAR: na myāyaṃ → na cāyaṃ (bj)
msgctxt "sn47.6:1.4"
msgid ""
"Sacejja mayaṃ gocare careyyāma sake pettike visaye, na myāyaṃ, sakuṇagghi, "
"alaṃ abhavissa, yadidaṃ—yuddhāyā’ti."
msgstr ""
"If today I’d roamed within my own territory, the domain of my fathers, this "
"hawk wouldn’t have been able to beat me by fighting.’"

msgctxt "sn47.6:1.5"
msgid "‘Ko pana te, lāpa, gocaro sako pettiko visayo’ti?"
msgstr "‘So, quail, what is your own territory, the domain of your fathers?’"

msgctxt "sn47.6:1.6"
msgid "‘Yadidaṃ—"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "sn47.6:1.7"
msgid "naṅgalakaṭṭhakaraṇaṃ leḍḍuṭṭhānan’ti."
msgstr "‘It’s a ploughed field covered with clods of earth.’"

#. VAR: asaṃvadamānā lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ pamuñci → avacamānā amuñci (sī1), avādamānā lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ pamuñci (syā1-3)
msgctxt "sn47.6:1.8"
msgid ""
"Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi sake bale apatthaddhā sake bale asaṃvadamānā "
"lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ pamuñci:"
msgstr ""
"Because of her own strength, the hawk was not daunted or intimidated. She "
"released the quail, saying:"

msgctxt "sn47.6:1.9"
msgid "‘gaccha kho tvaṃ, lāpa, tatrapi me gantvā na mokkhasī’ti."
msgstr "‘Go now, quail. But even there you won’t escape me!’"

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc2"></a>
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho, bhikkhave, lāpo sakuṇo naṅgalakaṭṭhakaraṇaṃ leḍḍuṭṭhānaṃ gantvā "
"mahantaṃ leḍḍuṃ abhiruhitvā sakuṇagghiṃ vadamāno aṭṭhāsi:"
msgstr ""
"Then the quail went to a ploughed field covered with clods of earth. He "
"climbed up a big clod, and standing there, he said to the hawk:"

#. VAR: dāni me → dāni (sī1)
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.2"
msgid "‘ehi kho dāni me, sakuṇagghi, ehi kho dāni me, sakuṇagghī’ti."
msgstr "‘Come get me, hawk! Come get me, hawk!’"

#. VAR: sannayha → sandhāya (bj, s1-3) | sannāyha (pts1)
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.3"
msgid ""
"Atha kho sā, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi sake bale apatthaddhā sake bale "
"asaṃvadamānā ubho pakkhe sannayha lāpaṃ sakuṇaṃ sahasā ajjhappattā."
msgstr ""
"Because of her own strength, the hawk was not daunted or intimidated. She "
"folded her wings and suddenly swooped down on the quail."

# BB has “inside that clod”. I am not really sure how a bird gets inside a clod of earth! Obviously it means “under” the clod, in the shelter of it.
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.4"
msgid ""
"Yadā kho, bhikkhave, aññāsi lāpo sakuṇo ‘bahuāgato kho myāyaṃ sakuṇagghī’ti, "
"atha tasseva leḍḍussa antaraṃ paccupādi."
msgstr ""
"When the quail knew that the hawk was nearly there, he slipped under that "
"clod."

# BB has “shattered”, but this is excessive. There’s nothing in the text that implies the hawk was killed or even injured; she just collided with the clod.
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.5"
msgid "Atha kho, bhikkhave, sakuṇagghi tattheva uraṃ paccatāḷesi."
msgstr "And the hawk crashed chest-first right there."

#. VAR: Evañhi taṃ → evaṃ hetaṃ (bj) | evañhetaṃ (s1-3)
msgctxt "sn47.6:2.6"
msgid "Evañhi taṃ, bhikkhave, hoti yo agocare carati paravisaye."
msgstr ""
"That’s what happens when you roam out of your territory into the domain of "
"others."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc3"></a>
msgctxt "sn47.6:3.1"
msgid "Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, mā agocare carittha paravisaye."
msgstr ""
"So, mendicants, don’t roam out of your own territory into the domain of "
"others."

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.2"
msgid ""
"Agocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ paravisaye lacchati māro otāraṃ, lacchati māro "
"ārammaṇaṃ."
msgstr ""
"If you roam out of your own territory into the domain of others, Māra will "
"find a vulnerability and get hold of you."

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.3"
msgid "Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo?"
msgstr "And what is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others?"

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.4"
msgid "Yadidaṃ—"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.5"
msgid "pañca kāmaguṇā."
msgstr "It’s the five kinds of sensual stimulation."

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.6"
msgid "Katame pañca?"
msgstr "What five?"

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.7"
msgid ""
"Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā, "
msgstr ""
"Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, "
"sensual, and arousing. "

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.8"
msgid "sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …"
msgstr "Sounds known by the ear …"

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.9"
msgid "ghānaviññeyyā gandhā … pe …"
msgstr "Smells known by the nose …"

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.10"
msgid "jivhāviññeyyā rasā … pe …"
msgstr "Tastes known by the tongue …"

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.11"
msgid ""
"kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā—"
msgstr ""
"Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, "
"sensual, and arousing."

msgctxt "sn47.6:3.12"
msgid "ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno agocaro paravisayo."
msgstr "This is not a mendicant’s own territory but the domain of others."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="pts-vp-pi" id="pts-vp-pi5.148"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc4"></a>
msgctxt "sn47.6:4.1"
msgid "Gocare, bhikkhave, caratha sake pettike visaye."
msgstr "You should roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers."

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.2"
msgid ""
"Gocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ sake pettike visaye na lacchati māro otāraṃ, na "
"lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ."
msgstr ""
"If you roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers, Māra won’"
"t find a vulnerability or get hold of you."

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.3"
msgid "Ko ca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo?"
msgstr "And what is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers?"

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.4"
msgid "Yadidaṃ—"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.5"
msgid "cattāro satipaṭṭhānā."
msgstr "It’s the four kinds of mindfulness meditation."

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.6"
msgid "Katame cattāro?"
msgstr "What four?"

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.7"
msgid ""
"Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, "
"vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ;"
msgstr ""
"It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, "
"aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world."

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.8"
msgid "vedanāsu … pe …"
msgstr "They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …"

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.9"
msgid "citte … pe …"
msgstr "mind …"

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.10"
msgid ""
"dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke "
"abhijjhādomanassaṃ—"
msgstr ""
"principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the "
"world."

msgctxt "sn47.6:4.11"
msgid "ayaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno gocaro sako pettiko visayo”ti."
msgstr "This is a mendicant’s own territory, the domain of the fathers.”"

#. </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "sn47.6:4.12"
msgid "Chaṭṭhaṃ."
msgstr ""
